# 7. Physical Interpretation

The activation function

[
g(\mathcal L) = 1 - \exp\left[-\left(\frac{\mathcal L}{\mathcal L_s}\right)^\nu\right]
]

is the complement of a Weibull survival law.

The inactive fraction is

[
S(\mathcal L) = 1 - g(\mathcal L)
              = \exp\left[-\left(\frac{\mathcal L}{\mathcal L_s}\right)^\nu\right].
]

For cosmology

[
\mathcal L = \frac{\ln(1+z)}{u_s}.
]

The activation factor therefore represents the fraction of curvature-memory domains that have become dynamically active as cumulative expansion history increases.

---

# 8. Limiting Regimes

At high redshift

[
g(z) \rightarrow 1.
]

Thus the expansion history approaches the standard matter-dominated behaviour.

At low redshift

[
g(z) \approx \left(\frac{z}{u_s}\right)^\nu.
]

This produces a small suppression of the effective matter contribution near the present epoch.

---

# 9. Mathematical Structure of the Activation Law

Define

[
M(\mathcal L) = -\ln(1-g).
]

Then

[
M(\mathcal L) = \left(\frac{\mathcal L}{\mathcal L_s}\right)^\nu.
]

Differentiating gives the scale-flow equation

[
\frac{dM}{d\ln \mathcal L} = \nu M.
]

The observable activation law therefore satisfies

[
\frac{dg}{d\mathcal L} = \nu \mathcal L^{\nu-1}(1-g).
]

---

# 10. Conclusions

We investigated a cosmological model in which the matter-sector contribution to the expansion rate is modulated by an activation function depending on accumulated expansion history.

Key results:

• Pantheon+ and DESI data favour the activation framework over the recovered (\Lambda)CDM baseline by (\Delta\chi^2 \approx -13)

• Equality-tied activation provides a compact parametrization with

[
\alpha \approx 0.48 - 0.52
]

• The model remains consistent with Gold-2017 growth measurements.

• The optimized equality-tied activation solution yields the lowest total (\chi^2) among the models tested.

The preferred activation scale corresponds to a redshift

[
z_s \approx 0.21
]

occurring after matter–(\Lambda) equality near

[
z_{eq} \approx 0.50.
]

Further work is required to investigate the theoretical origin of the activation law and to test its consistency with full early-universe constraints.

